batch_size = 32
color_channels = 3

# Load and prepare the dataset for use with a TensorFlow model

    training_data_path,
    shuffle=True,
    image_size=(image_dimensions, image_dimensions),
    batch_size=batch_size
)

# Function to retrieve the label name from the index
def fetch_label(index):
    return categories[index]  # Assuming 'categories' has been defined as dataset.class_names

# Fetch and display a single batch from the dataset
for images_batch, labels_batch in dataset.take(1):
    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))  # Set the size of the figure for the images
    chosen_indices = np.random.choice(images_batch.shape[0], size=5, replace=False)  # Randomly select 5 indices

    for position, image_index in enumerate(chosen_indices):
        plt.subplot(1, 5, position + 1)  # Arrange images in a row of 5
        plt.imshow(images_batch[image_index].numpy().astype("uint8"))  # Display image at selected index
        plt.title(fetch_label(labels_batch[image_index]))  # Set title to the corresponding label
        plt.axis("off")  # Optionally, uncomment this to hide the axes

    plt.tight_layout()  # Adjust layout to not overlap images
    plt.show()
    break  # Exit the loop after the first batch

# Function to retrieve the name of a category by its index
def retrieve_label(index):
    return categories[index]  # Ensure 'categories' corresponds to dataset.class_names

# Configure the plot to display images with customized aesthetics
plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))  # Set the dimension of the figure (width, height)

# Process a single batch from the dataset
for images_batch, labels_batch in dataset.take(1):
    selected_indices = np.random.choice(images_batch.shape[0], size=5, replace=False)  # Randomly pick 5 indices
    for position, image_index in enumerate(selected_indices):
        plot_area = plt.subplot(1, 5, position + 1)  # Define subplot area
        plot_area.imshow(images_batch[image_index].numpy().astype("uint8"))  # Display the image
        plot_area.set_title(retrieve_label(labels_batch[image_index]), color='purple')  # Set the title with a purple color
        
        # Keep the axis visible
        plot_area.axis('on')

        # Customize axis labels and tick marks
        plot_area.xaxis.label.set_color('purple')
        plot_area.yaxis.label.set_color('purple')
        plot_area.tick_params(axis='both', colors='purple')

        # Customize subplot background and grid
        plot_area.set_facecolor('black')  # Background color set to black
        plot_area.grid(True, color='purple', linestyle='--', linewidth=0.5)  # Purple grid lines

    plt.tight_layout(pad=0.5)  # Apply tight layout with specified padding
    plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.1, hspace=0)  # Adjust space between plots
    plt.show()
    break  # Exit after the first batch to prevent processing additional batches

In [7]:
def split_dataset(dataset, train_fraction=0.8, validation_fraction=0.1, test_fraction=0.1, enable_shuffle=True, shuffle_buffer_size=10000):
    """
    Splits the dataset into training, validation, and test subsets.
    
    Parameters:
        dataset: The complete dataset to be split.
        train_fraction: Fraction of the dataset to be used as the training set.
        validation_fraction: Fraction of the dataset to be used as the validation set.
        test_fraction: Fraction of the dataset to be used as the test set.
        enable_shuffle: Boolean to determine whether to shuffle the dataset.
        shuffle_buffer_size: Number of items in the dataset from which to sample when shuffling.

    Returns:
        A tuple containing (train_dataset, validation_dataset, dataset_for_testing).
    """

    total_size = len(dataset)
    
    if enable_shuffle:
        dataset = dataset.shuffle(shuffle_buffer_size, seed=12)  # Seed for reproducibility
    
    train_size = int(train_fraction * total_size)
    validation_size = int(validation_fraction * total_size)
    
    train_dataset = dataset.take(train_size)
    validation_dataset = dataset.skip(train_size).take(validation_size)
    dataset_for_testing = dataset.skip(train_size).skip(validation_size)
    
    return train_dataset, validation_dataset, dataset_for_testing

# Prepare the training dataset with caching, shuffling, and prefetching to optimize loading speed
train_dataset = train_dataset.cache().shuffle(1000).prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

# Prepare the validation dataset similarly to ensure efficient validation loops
validation_dataset = validation_dataset.cache().shuffle(1000).prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

# Prepare the test dataset with the same optimizations as the training and validation datasets
dataset_for_testing = dataset_for_testing.cache().shuffle(1000).prefetch(buffer_size=tf.data.AUTOTUNE)

Augmenting Data¶

In [10]:
# Define image size globally if not already defined
image_size = 256  # Ensure this matches your dataset's expected image dimension

# Rescaling layer to resize and normalize image data
rescaling = tf.keras.Sequential([
    layers.Resizing(image_size, image_size),  # Resize images to a consistent shape
    layers.Rescaling(1./255)  # Normalize pixel values to [0, 1]
])

# Data augmentation layer to introduce randomness in the dataset during training to improve generalization
data_augmentation = tf.keras.Sequential([
    layers.RandomFlip("horizontal_and_vertical"),  # Randomly flip images horizontally and vertically
    layers.RandomRotation(0.2),  # Randomly rotate images by +/- 20%
    layers.RandomZoom(0.1)  # Randomly zoom into images up to 10%
])

Model¶

In [11]:
# Define the number of classes and input shape for the model
number_of_classes = 4
input_shape_param = (batch_size, image_size, image_size, color_channels)

# Define the model using a descriptive variable name
neural_network_model = models.Sequential([
    rescaling,  # Rescaling layer defined earlier
    data_augmentation,  # Data augmentation layer defined earlier
    layers.Conv2D(32, (3, 3), activation='relu', input_shape=input_shape_param[1:]),  # Use slice to remove batch size from input shape
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(64, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Conv2D(128, (3, 3), activation='relu'),
    layers.MaxPooling2D((2, 2)),
    layers.Flatten(),
    layers.Dense(512, activation='relu'),
    layers.Dense(number_of_classes, activation='softmax'),
])

# Build the model using the revised input shape variable
neural_network_model.build(input_shape=(None, image_size, image_size, color_channels))  # None used for variable batch size flexibility

# Output the model configuration
neural_network_model.summary()

In [27]:
def predict_image_class(model, image):
    image_array = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(image)
    image_array = tf.expand_dims(image_array, 0)
    predictions = model.predict(image_array)
    predicted_label = categories[np.argmax(predictions[0])]
    confidence_level = round(100 * np.max(predictions[0]), 2)
    return predicted_label, confidence_level
plt.figure(figsize=(15, 15))

for images_batch,labels_batch in dataset_for_testing.take(1):

        plt.title(f"Actual: {actual_label} \n Predicted: {predicted_label} \n Confidence: {confidence_level}%")

SVM¶

In [33]:
# Define classes and corresponding labels
class_labels = {'no_tumor': 0, 'pituitary_tumor': 1}

# Initialize lists to store images and labels
X = []
Y = []

# Iterate over classes and images to load data
for class_name, label in class_labels.items():
    class_path = os.path.join(unzip_target, 'Training', class_name)
    for image_file in os.listdir(class_path):
        img = cv2.imread(os.path.join(class_path, image_file), cv2.IMREAD_GRAYSCALE)
        img = cv2.resize(img, (200, 200))
        X.append(img)
        Y.append(label)

# Convert lists to NumPy arrays
X = np.array(X)
Y = np.array(Y)

# Reshape the input images for compatibility with machine learning models
X_flat = X.reshape(len(X), -1)

# Check unique labels and their counts
unique_labels = np.unique(Y)
label_counts = pd.Series(Y).value_counts()

# Print shapes of the original and updated data
print("Original Image Data Shape:", X.shape)
print("Updated Image Data Shape:", X_flat.shape)

# Split the data into training and testing sets
x_train, x_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X_flat, Y, random_state=10, test_size=.20)

# Print shapes of the training and testing sets
print("Training Set Shape:", x_train.shape)
print("Testing Set Shape:", x_test.shape)

# Feature Scaling: Normalize pixel values to range [0, 1]
print("Before Scaling - Max and Min Values:")
print("Training Set - Max:", x_train.max(), "Min:", x_train.min())
print("Testing Set - Max:", x_test.max(), "Min:", x_test.min())

x_train_scaled = x_train / 255.0
x_test_scaled = x_test / 255.0

print("After Scaling - Max and Min Values:")
print("Training Set - Max:", x_train_scaled.max(), "Min:", x_train_scaled.min())
print("Testing Set - Max:", x_test_scaled.max(), "Min:", x_test_scaled.min())

### Evaluation
